I Thought I Knew What I Was Getting Into
Press enter or click to view image in full size

I spent six months building a bot that publishes articles across 10+ Chinese platforms. Let me tell you what the real bottleneck was. It wasn’t CAPTCHAs. It wasn’t anti-bot detection. It wasn’t even rate limiting. It was the WYSIWYG editors — five different implementations, zero documentation for how to script them, and each one ready to corrupt your content if you touch it wrong.
Every major Chinese content platform uses a different rich text editor. CSDN uses CKEditor wrapped in Vue. Baijiahao uses Baidu’s own UEditor — a project that hasn’t been meaningfully updated since 2019 but still runs millions of CMS instances. Toutiao and Jianshu use Quill with custom modules. And in my own pipeline, the Medium editor is a custom-built Operational Transformation engine that actively fights automation.
The common thread: none of them want you to script them. There’s no API for posting. There’s no headless mode. There’s just a contenteditable div and a README that says “use our SDK” — which requires a browser and a human.
So I reverse-engineered each one. Here’s what I found.
CKEditor — The Friendly One (Until Vue Gets in the Way)
CSDN runs CKEditor 4. CKEditor 4 has one of the cleanest APIs in the WYSIWYG world:
CKEDITOR.instances.editor.setData('<h2>Hello World</h2><p>This is my content.</p>');Clean. Simple. It handles HTML sanitization, undo history, and dirty-state tracking. It’s about as civilized as a rich text editor gets.
The problem is that CSDN wraps CKEditor inside a Vue component. If you call setData() before the Vue component finishes mounting, the editor instance doesn't exist yet. And if you call it after, Vue's reactivity might overwrite your content when its own data watcher fires.
The fix is a polling loop:
async function waitForCKEditor(timeout = 10000) {
const start = Date.now();
while (Date.now() - start < timeout) {
if (typeof CKEDITOR !== 'undefined' && CKEDITOR.instances.editor) {
return CKEDITOR.instances.editor;
}
await new Promise(r => setTimeout(r, 200));
}
throw new Error('CKEditor did not initialize');
}const editor = await waitForCKEditor();
editor.setData(myContent);
editor.fire('contentChanged'); // Tell Vue something changedKey lesson: editors inside SPA frameworks need the framework’s watcher to know about changes, not just the editor itself.
UEditor — The Abandoned Warhorse
Baidu’s UEditor is everywhere on Chinese CMS platforms. It was last meaningfully updated in 2019. It has no npm package, no reliable CDN, and its API is a mix of documented commands and internal methods you discover by reading minified source.
Baijiahao uses UEditor with a custom toolbar and a weird iframe-based embedded mode. The “official” way to set content:
UE.getEditor('editor').setContent(html);This works. Sometimes. The issue is that setContent() triggers an internal parse that strips or mangles certain HTML structures — nested lists, specific inline styles, and weirdly, <section> tags.
After digging through the minified source, I found a more reliable path:
const editor = UE.getEditor('editor');
editor.ready(() => {
editor.execCommand('insertHtml', myHtml);
editor.fireEvent('contentchange');
});But even execCommand has quirks. UEditor maintains an internal undo stack. If you call setContent() twice, the second call can corrupt the first. And there's no reliable way to clear the undo history. I once spent three hours debugging why my content was showing random <style> tags — turns out UEditor's internal parser was appending them from a previous call.
Quill — The Contenteditable Trap
Quill looks modern and well-designed from the outside. Its delta format for representing document changes is elegant. But that elegance comes at a cost: it fights you when you try to bypass it.
Setting innerHTML on a Quill-editable div is the fastest way to break it. Quill uses MutationObserver to track changes. If the DOM changes without going through Quill's API, the observer gets confused and the document state diverges from Quill's internal model.
The safe way:
const quill = Quill.find(document.querySelector('.ql-editor'));
quill.clipboard.dangerouslyPasteHTML(0, myHtml);Yes, the method is literally called “dangerouslyPasteHTML”. Quill knows this is dangerous. When you paste HTML directly, Quill runs it through its clipboard matchers, which can strip or transform content in unexpected ways. Lists might become paragraphs. Inline styles might disappear. Code blocks might lose their language tags — though the code itself stays intact.
The trick I learned: paste HTML that matches what Quill’s own toolbar would produce. Use <p> not <div>. Use <strong> not <span style="font-weight: bold">. Quill's matchers recognize these native patterns and preserve them.
Medium — The Anti-Automation Pro
Medium’s editor deserves its own category. It’s built on a custom Operational Transformation engine — similar to what Google Docs uses. This means every keystroke is a data structure, not just a DOM mutation.
Medium actively blocks automation at multiple layers:

• Its content gate rejects non-browser HTTP clients (403 on puppeteer without stealth plugins)

• The editor state is managed client-side via OT; pasting the same content twice doubles everything

• navigator.clipboard.write() combined with a real Ctrl+V works exactly once per session — try again and the OT diff breaks

• Refreshing the page reverts your content because the OT state hasn’t been committed
The one reliable approach I found:
// This works exactly once
await page.evaluate(async (html) => {
const blob = new Blob([html], { type: 'text/html' });
await navigator.clipboard.write([new ClipboardItem({ 'text/html': blob })]);
}, html);bodyEl.click();
await page.keyboard.press('Control+V');If you paste again in the same session, the OT diff doubles the content. And if you refresh, the content reverts because the OT state hasn’t been committed to the server yet. The Medium editor is the reason I added a word-count gate in my pipeline — if the first paste produces fewer than 1,200 words, I start a new draft entirely rather than trying to fix it in-place.
The Detection Switch
After fighting all of these, here’s what I learned about reliability:
CKEditor — setData() + fire('contentChanged') — 95% reliable
UEditor — execCommand('insertHtml') — 85% reliable
Quill — dangerouslyPasteHTML() — 90% reliable
Medium OT — Clipboard paste (one shot) — 70% reliable
Generic contenteditable — execCommand('insertHTML') — 60% reliable
My current approach is a simple detection switch:
function detectEditor() {
if (typeof CKEDITOR !== 'undefined') return 'ckeditor';
if (typeof UE !== 'undefined') return 'ueditor';
if (typeof Quill !== 'undefined') return 'quill';
if (document.querySelector('[data-medium-editor]')) return 'medium';
return 'generic';
}No framework. No dependencies. Just check for the global.
The universal fallback for everything else: clipboard paste. Ctrl+V works in every editor because it triggers the editor's own paste handler — the same one human writers use. It's slow and unreliable for huge documents, and Medium's OT system makes it a one-shot deal, but it beats every other approach when the editor has no public API.
Things I Still Haven’t Figured Out
I still don’t know how to reliably handle the Medium editor for edits. One paste works. Two pastes break. And I’m pretty sure there’s a hidden state machine inside the OT system that resets only when the Medium servers decide to sync on their own schedule.
Also — if your platform uses a custom editor built on Slate or Prosemirror and you want to discourage bots: don’t fight them. Just use MutationObserver. It’ll break on the first innerHTML write and they’ll give up.
If you’ve reverse-engineered a WYSIWYG editor I haven’t tried, or if you know the right way to reset Medium’s OT state programmatically — I’d love to hear about it.
